    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and the principal isnt going down as much as i thought it would even though i pay the same amount every month. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated on a declining balance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're seeing this because your loan is likely using an **interest-first** payment schedule, which is the standard for most student loans. Every dollar you pay goes toward interest until the principal balance drops enough that your monthly payment can start reducing the principal significantly.\n\nThink of it like a house with a very high mortgage rate: if you pay the same amount every month, the early years are mostly paying off the \"interest tax\" that the bank charges you for borrowing the money.\n\nTo see how this works, imagine a loan with a $10,000 balance and a 6% interest rate. In the first month, the bank charges you about $50 in interest ($10,000 * 0.06 / 12). If you pay $200 total, only $150 goes toward the actual principal, so your balance only drops to $9,850.\n\nOnce your balance drops, the interest charge for the next month becomes slightly smaller, meaning more of your fixed payment goes toward the principal. This is why the principal reduction feels slow at first but speeds up as you get closer to paying off the debt.\n\nIf you want to speed up the principal",
      "source": "target",
